\begin_layout Title
Optimal discrimination of a class of mixed states with a fixed rate of inconclus
ive outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Vadim Yerokhin, Andi Shehu, and János A.
 Bergou
\end_layout

\begin_layout Affiliation
Department of Physics and Astronomy, Hunter College of the City University
 of New York, 695 Park Avenue, New York, NY 10065, USA 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Recently the problem of optimal state discrimination with a Fixed Rate of
 Inconclusive Outcomes (FRIO strategy) has been solved for two pure quantum
 states and a few other highly symmetric cases.
 The strategy optimally interpolates between the Minimum Error discrimination
 strategy (fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes is zero) and the Unambiguous
 Discrimination strategy (fixed rate of inconclusive outcomes is the critical
 rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{c}$
\end_inset

, for which the error rate is zero).
 Here we extend the FRIO strategy to two mixed states, whose eigenvectors
 in their spectral representation form a Jordan basis.
 We derive the minimum error rate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{E}$
\end_inset

 for a fixed inconclusive rate 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and, in particular, the optimal distribution of the total 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 over the Jordan subspaces.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is varied between the two limits, 
\begin_inset Formula $0<Q<Q_{c}$
\end_inset

, a structure with multiple thresholds, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}^{(th)}(=0)<Q_{2}^{(th)}<\ldots<Q_{N}^{(th)}<Q_{c}$
\end_inset

, emerges.
 In the region, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{1}^{(th)}<Q<Q_{2}^{(th)}$
\end_inset

, one subspace receives the total 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 Above the second threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is shared by two subspaces, above the third threshold by three, etc.
 Above the last threshold, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{N}^{(th)}<Q<Q_{c}$
\end_inset

, all subspaces participate in sharing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

.
 The optimal measurement can be projective or a POVM and we give the conditions
 for the transition between the projective and POVM regimes.
 The results are illustrated on the example of two rank 3 mixed states.
 
\end_layout

