\begin_layout Standard
We first present a brief review of the method developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bagan"

\end_inset

 for the two pure state optimal FRIO problem since the rest of the paper
 relies heavily on this method.
 We derive the maximum probability of success or, equivalently, the minimum
 probability of error in identifying the states, when a certain fixed rate
 of inconclusive outcomes is allowed.
 By varying the inconclusive rate, the scheme optimally interpolates between
 Unambiguous and Minimum Error discrimination (UD and ME), the two standard
 approaches to quantum state discrimination.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all of these scenarios (UD, ME or FRIO) one is given a system which is
 promised to be prepared in one of two known pure states, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=\ke{\psi_{1}}\br{\psi_{1}}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}=\ke{\psi_{2}}\br{\psi_{2}}$
\end_inset

, but we don't know which.
 The pure states are prepared with prior probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, respectively, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 It is well known that two pure states can be discriminated both unambiguously
 and with minimum error.
 The optimal (minimal) inconclusive rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 for UD has been derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ivanovic,dieks,peres,jaeger"

\end_inset

, and is given by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Since two pure states can be unambiguously discriminated, the critical
 probability $Q_{
\backslash
rm c}$ coincides %with the optimal failure probability~$Q^{
