\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q_{{\rm c}}=\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
\eta_{1}+\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{{\displaystyle \eta_{1}<\frac{\cos^{2}\theta}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(l)}}},}\\[0.7em]
\eta_{2}+\eta_{1}\cos^{2}\theta,\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}>{\displaystyle \frac{1}{1+\cos^{2}\theta}\equiv\eta_{1}^{(r)}}},}\\[0.7em]
2\sqrt{\eta_{1}\eta_{2}}\cos\theta\equiv Q_{0},\mbox{if \ensuremath{\eta_{1}^{(l)}\le\eta_{1}\le\eta_{1}^{(r)}}}\ ,
\end{array}\right.\label{Qmax}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $|\langle\psi_{1}|\psi_{2}\rangle|\equiv\cos\theta$
\end_inset

 is the overlap of the states.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal (minimal) error rate for ME has been derived in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "helstrom"

\end_inset

 and is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{{\rm E}}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-\sqrt{1-4\eta_{1}\eta_{2}\cos^{2}\theta}\;\right).\label{PE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For a compact derivation of these basic results see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bergourev"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the FRIO strategy we want three measurement outcomes, one that we identify
 with the first state, one that we identify with the second state and one
 that we do not identify with a state, corresponding to the inconclusive
 outcome.
 Therefore, we look for the solution as a three-element POVM (Positive Operator
 Valued Measure), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{1}+\Pi_{2}+\Pi_{0}=I\ ,\label{POVM}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the identity operator in the Hilbert space of the states.
 We identify a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{1}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{2}$
\end_inset

) with the first (second) state, while a click in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi_{0}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the inconclusive outcome.
 We wish to optimize (maximize) the success rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}=\eta_{1}tr[\Pi_{1}\rho_{1}]+\eta_{2}tr[\Pi_{2}\rho_{2}]$
\end_inset

 or, equivalently, minimize the error rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=\eta_{1}tr[\Pi_{2}\rho_{1}]+\eta_{2}tr[\Pi_{1}\rho_{2}]$
\end_inset

, for a fixed failure rate, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Q=tr[\Pi_{0}(\eta_{1}\rho_{1}+\eta_{2}\rho_{2})]\ .\label{Q}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq Q\leq Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 and for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=Q_{{\rm c}}$
\end_inset

 the FRIO strategy reduces to UD with 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}=0$
\end_inset

 while for 
\begin_inset Formula $Q=0$
\end_inset

 the FRIO strategy reduces to ME with the error rate given by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "PE"

\end_inset

.
 For a given intermediate value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 the strategy minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{e}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

