\begin_layout Standard
In this and the next section we consider the FRIO discrimination of two
 mixed states that exhibit a Jordan structure.
 The two states, with their respective 
\emph on
prior
\emph default
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, are given in spectral (diagonal) form as, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\rho_{1} & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}r_{i}\vert r_{i}\rangle\langle r_{i}\vert\nonumber \\
\rho_{2} & = & \sum_{i=1}^{N}s_{i}\vert s_{i}\rangle\langle s_{i}\vert\ .\label{rho1and2}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle r_{i}\vert r_{j}\rangle=\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle s_{i}\vert s_{j}\rangle=\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 Each density matrix has rank 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and together they span a 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space.
 We assume that the Jordan condition, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle r_{i}\vert s_{j}\rangle=\delta_{ij}\cos\theta_{i}\ ,\label{jordan}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

holds so the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\vert r_{i}\rangle,\vert s_{i}\rangle\vert i=1,\ldots,N\rangle\}$
\end_inset

 forms a Jordan basis for the 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space.
\end_layout

