\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 with 
\emph on
prior
\emph default
 probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{1}r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}s_{i}$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The full discrimination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2}$
\end_inset

 can be accomplished by performing the discrimination in each subspace independe
ntly of the others, i.e., by discriminating 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert r_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vert s_{i}\rangle$
\end_inset

 in each subspace which is much simpler than the original problem.
 A physical implementation of this scheme is provided, e.g., by the transmission
 of two input states over several optical fibers.
 Each fiber contains two degrees of freedom, that could be two orthogonal
